Phase 21 second-pass review — archive
=====================================
timestamp: 2026-04-18 20:15 +0800
branch: make-it-ts

Scope: first-principles review of the full Phase 21 stack (slices
A-F + the first hotfix commit). Driven end-to-end with an inline
wire harness that exercises every restored method, plus ad-hoc CLI
probes and edge-case CLI error paths.


Findings that required a code change
----------------------------------------------------------------

1. BLOCKER — wire error code -32601 Method not found was not
   reachable. Router threw `new Error('Method not found: X')`
   which `mapToWireError` collapsed into -32603 Internal error.
   The entire production-surface regression test assertion
   (`.not.toBe(-32601)`) was therefore a no-op: it would have
   stayed green even if Slice A's merge had silently dropped a
   handler again. Same story for "Session not found". Fixed by
   introducing typed WireMethodNotFoundError / WireSessionNotFoundError
   in wire-protocol/errors.ts, teaching mapToWireError about them
   (-32601 / -32000 respectively), and rewriting the production
   surface test to fail hard on -32601 via an explicit throw.

2. MAJOR — `kimi info` reported kimi-cli version 0.0.0 while
   `kimi --version` reported 0.0.1. The info command's
   readPackageVersion assumed the TypeScript source layout (three
   levels above import.meta.dirname), but after tsdown bundled
   everything into dist/index.mjs `import.meta.dirname` points at
   `dist/`, making the three-levels-up path land on the monorepo
   root package.json. Fixed by walking candidate paths
   (`../package.json`, `../../package.json`, `../../../package.json`)
   and picking the first one whose `name === "@moonshot-ai/cli"`.

3. MAJOR — concurrent `session.setModel` calls against the same
   session could race through the `closeSession → resumeSession`
   dance. Added a per-session promise-chain mutex
   (`swapLocks: Map<string, Promise<unknown>>`) around
   `wireRebuildRuntimeForModel`. Unrelated sessions still swap in
   parallel.


